- Then she gave me something.

1228
00:43:53,026 --> 00:43:55,196
- They have this shopping bag.
- A shopping bag?

1229
00:43:55,356 --> 00:43:57,626
- Right. They have that bag.
- Yes. A paper bag.

1230
00:43:58,126 --> 00:44:00,395
I said thank you and left.

1231
00:44:00,396 --> 00:44:01,536
I got on the bus after that.

1232
00:44:01,636 --> 00:44:05,436
On the bus, I looked in the bag to see what was in it.

1233
00:44:05,706 --> 00:44:07,975
She gave me the cookies.

1234
00:44:07,976 --> 00:44:11,645
And it had the receipt on the bag.

1235
00:44:11,646 --> 00:44:14,006
There was a message behind the receipt.

1236
00:44:14,376 --> 00:44:16,476
- She wrote it in a hurry.
- What did she say?

1237
00:44:16,616 --> 00:44:18,846
- Let me read it for you.
- Did you bring it?

1238
00:44:19,686 --> 00:44:23,016
(The letter that was written on the receipt.)

1239
00:44:23,656 --> 00:44:24,785
"Dear Mr. Big Star."

1240
00:44:24,786 --> 00:44:26,155
- That's hard to read.
- "Mr. Choi, you must be sick of..."

1241
00:44:26,156 --> 00:44:27,525
"this kind of message."

1242
00:44:27,526 --> 00:44:30,596
"I couldn't get any private education during my school days."

1243
00:44:30,696 --> 00:44:35,165
"Thanks to your EBS lectures,"

1244
00:44:35,166 --> 00:44:37,236
"I got a lot of help from them."

1245
00:44:37,366 --> 00:44:39,935
"It was a shame that we couldn't do a tteokbokki party,"

1246
00:44:39,936 --> 00:44:42,775
"but it was so nice to meet you by chance today."

1247
00:44:42,776 --> 00:44:44,446
"Thanks from my heart."

1248
00:44:44,576 --> 00:44:46,506
"From your student on the web."

1249
00:44:47,006 --> 00:44:50,516
This is the happiness that you can't trade for any money.

1250
00:44:50,776 --> 00:44:52,985
It was a chance to feel that again.

1251
00:44:52,986 --> 00:44:55,985
- I thought I was experiencing...
- The stars.

1252
00:44:55,986 --> 00:44:57,825
that happiness thanks to the stars, my students.

1253
00:44:57,826 --> 00:44:59,355
- It was such a happy moment.
- That's cool.

1254
00:44:59,356 --> 00:45:00,786
There's nothing that makes me happier.

1255
00:45:01,126 --> 00:45:02,956
I visited Gyeongju to give a lecture.

1256
00:45:03,156 --> 00:45:04,825
- I do a lot of lectures.
- To Gyeongju.

1257
00:45:04,826 --> 00:45:08,566
I heard that it was amazing. The whole city was paralyzed.

1258
00:45:08,796 --> 00:45:10,436
Even the buses stopped running.

1259
00:45:11,336 --> 00:45:12,506
- Goodness.
- See?

1260
00:45:13,906 --> 00:45:17,675
(The hall is filled with people.)

1261
00:45:17,676 --> 00:45:19,405
- People are standing in the back.
- It was filled with so many people.

1262
00:45:19,406 --> 00:45:21,246
Why does it look like it's been Photoshopped?

1263
00:45:21,846 --> 00:45:24,615
- Are they standing at the back?
- That's taken from the side.

1264
00:45:24,616 --> 00:45:26,486
And that's from the front. I got two pictures from that day.

1265
00:45:26,786 --> 00:45:28,056
So I went to Gyeongju.

1266
00:45:28,256 --> 00:45:31,885
- And there were 3,000 people.
- What was it about?

1267
00:45:31,886 --> 00:45:33,225
There's no place for 3,000...

1268
00:45:33,226 --> 00:45:34,525
- in Gyeongju.
- It was a lecture.

1269
00:45:34,526 --> 00:45:36,525
- A history lecture?
- So there was this center.

1270
00:45:36,526 --> 00:45:39,966
It's the biggest place there, and I took two halls of that place.

1271
00:45:40,066 --> 00:45:42,666
There were 1,200 people there, and there were no seats.

1272
00:45:42,836 --> 00:45:46,065
They came to the lecture as a family.

1273
00:45:46,066 --> 00:45:48,006
Especially, there were many elementary school students.

1274
00:45:48,176 --> 00:45:50,175
When the lecture was done,

1275
00:45:50,176 --> 00:45:51,945
no one left.

1276
00:45:51,946 --> 00:45:53,276
- They didn't leave.
- Why?

1277
00:45:53,376 --> 00:45:54,745
- They didn't want to leave.
- To get my autograph.

1278
00:45:54,746 --> 00:45:55,946
Right. You gave autographs.

1279
00:45:56,116 --> 00:46:00,185
And seriously, it took me more than five hours to give autographs.

1280
00:46:00,186 --> 00:46:01,655
- My gosh.
- Ho Dong set...

1281
00:46:01,656 --> 00:46:03,156
a Guinness World Record for shaking hands.

1282
00:46:04,056 --> 00:46:05,455
The next day,

1283
00:46:05,456 --> 00:46:07,385
- Five hours is a long time.
- I tried to raise my hand,

1284
00:46:07,386 --> 00:46:09,025
- but I couldn't.
- Of course.

1285
00:46:09,026 --> 00:46:10,756
My brain couldn't control my arm.

1286
00:46:10,926 --> 00:46:13,296
But there was a reason why I did that for five hours.

1287
00:46:13,426 --> 00:46:14,595
This happened once.

1288
00:46:14,596 --> 00:46:16,866
I once went to a baseball game with my daughter.

1289
00:46:16,936 --> 00:46:18,105
We were at the stadium,

1290
00:46:18,106 --> 00:46:20,036
and my daughter's favorite player was passing by.

1291
00:46:20,236 --> 00:46:23,436
When he was passing by, my daughter called that player.

1292
00:46:23,636 --> 00:46:25,376
She called like this. "Hee Chul!"

1293
00:46:25,646 --> 00:46:28,545
Then the player looked at my daughter like this,

1294
00:46:28,546 --> 00:46:29,675
then he smiled like this.

1295
00:46:29,676 --> 00:46:31,716
He smiled like this.

1296
00:46:32,486 --> 00:46:33,786
And my daughter was happy all day long.

1297
00:46:34,516 --> 00:46:35,816
All day long.

1298
00:46:36,056 --> 00:46:37,156
When I saw that,

1299
00:46:38,056 --> 00:46:40,686
I learned that even a small gesture...

1300
00:46:41,126 --> 00:46:43,895
could become a significant memory for someone.

1301
00:46:43,896 --> 00:46:46,866
So when elementary kids come to me for autographs,

1302
00:46:47,126 --> 00:46:48,295
I find them so cute.

1303
00:46:48,296 --> 00:46:50,436
It's just about 30 seconds.

1304
00:46:50,596 --> 00:46:53,305
But even for that 30 seconds, I try to do my best.

1305
00:46:53,306 --> 00:46:55,635
Excuse me, Star Ho Dong. I'll call you Big Star Ho Dong.

1306
00:46:55,636 --> 00:46:57,475
- I got breaking news.
- What is it?

1307
00:46:57,476 --> 00:47:00,376
It says you're saying only the nice things about you.

1308
00:47:00,776 --> 00:47:02,976
- According to Ye Won, - Yes?

1309
00:47:03,276 --> 00:47:05,616
- you're so luxurious.
- Goodness.

1310
00:47:06,116 --> 00:47:08,615
He complained about not being able to go to the Tower Palace.

1311
00:47:08,616 --> 00:47:10,516
- Are you going to Hannam-dong?
- He...

1312
00:47:10,786 --> 00:47:13,685
- Ye Won. Tell us about it.
- He does so many lectures.

1313
00:47:13,686 --> 00:47:15,325
He makes a lot of talent donations.

1314
00:47:15,326 --> 00:47:17,225
- He's on many shows.
- He does a lot of good things.

1315
00:47:17,226 --> 00:47:18,895
His books are always in the bestselling list.

1316
00:47:18,896 --> 00:47:20,125
So I'm curious about it.

1317
00:47:20,126 --> 00:47:22,066
"How much money does he have?"

1318
00:47:22,396 --> 00:47:25,205
I've been working with him for five years.

1319
00:47:25,206 --> 00:47:28,006
And I get to see what he wears when we're done with the shoot.

1320
00:47:28,976 --> 00:47:31,145
He wears old training pants...

1321
00:47:31,146 --> 00:47:33,175
and slippers.

1322
00:47:33,176 --> 00:47:36,675
But there's this thing that he spends a lot on.

1323
00:47:36,676 --> 00:47:37,815
- Watches?
- Watches?

1324
00:47:37,816 --> 00:47:39,346
- He's not wearing a watch.
- That is...

1325
00:47:39,816 --> 00:47:40,945
- Cars?
- He's not wearing a watch.

1326
00:47:40,946 --> 00:47:42,116
- his glasses.
- Cars?

1327
00:47:42,556 --> 00:47:44,015
- His glasses?
- Glasses?

1328
00:47:44,016 --> 00:47:46,585
- Is that so?
- This has changed...

1329
00:47:46,586 --> 00:47:48,996
- as he became popular.
- My goodness.

1330
00:47:49,156 --> 00:47:51,065
Five years ago, when we worked together,

1331
00:47:51,066 --> 00:47:54,125
- he had 1 or 2 glasses.
- The numbers are increasing?

1332
00:47:54,126 --> 00:47:56,495
But after five years,

1333
00:47:56,496 --> 00:47:59,806
he has lots of glasses.

1334
00:48:00,266 --> 00:48:02,235
- And he always wears new ones.
- Is that so?

1335
00:48:02,236 --> 00:48:05,075
This is what he does with his glasses.

1336
00:48:05,076 --> 00:48:06,375
- It depends on the color he wears.
- He switches his glasses.

1337
00:48:06,376 --> 00:48:07,475
- He must have tens of them.
- That's possible.

1338
00:48:07,476 --> 00:48:09,415
- Do you have bad eyesight?
- Well...

1339
00:48:09,416 --> 00:48:10,975
I'm a lecturer.

1340
00:48:10,976 --> 00:48:12,985
There are chapters from 1 to 5.

1341
00:48:12,986 --> 00:48:14,185
I have to go by the curriculum.

1342
00:48:14,186 --> 00:48:17,156
And the students might find my face boring.

1343
00:48:17,256 --> 00:48:18,525
But there's nothing I can show them.

1344
00:48:18,526 --> 00:48:19,726
So I thought about what I could do.

1345
00:48:20,456 --> 00:48:22,296
I should at least change my glasses.

1346
00:48:23,096 --> 00:48:24,465
- My glasses at least.
- That's nice.

1347
00:48:24,466 --> 00:48:27,196
So I bought some special glasses.

1348
00:48:27,396 --> 00:48:29,596
Some might say, "What's that?"

1349
00:48:29,766 --> 00:48:31,965
- I look for those.
- Are those not prescribed?

1350
00:48:31,966 --> 00:48:33,766
- No, they're not.
- There are no lenses.

1351
00:48:34,006 --> 00:48:35,675
- It's not there.
- The glasses don't have lenses.

1352
00:48:35,676 --> 00:48:37,006
- They don't have lenses.
- They were for fashion?

1353
00:48:37,276 --> 00:48:38,775
I'm not wearing it for myself.

1354
00:48:38,776 --> 00:48:40,805
- It's for the students.
- Right.

1355
00:48:40,806 --> 00:48:42,615
- I want to entertain them.
- That makes sense.

1356
00:48:42,616 --> 00:48:44,215
The first lesson ends, and on the second lesson,

1357
00:48:44,216 --> 00:48:45,415
they would think, "What glasses will he wear now?"

1358
00:48:45,416 --> 00:48:47,346
I thought you were wearing your glasses upside down today.

1359
00:48:47,916 --> 00:48:49,255
- That's right.
- He wants to show a variety.

1360
00:48:49,256 --> 00:48:50,455
I wanted to give them that impression.

1361
00:48:50,456 --> 00:48:52,125
- You brought your glasses?
- Let's see them.

1362
00:48:52,126 --> 00:48:53,726
- I brought them.
- Let's see.

1363
00:48:53,956 --> 00:48:55,195
I just brought half of them today.

1364
00:48:55,196 --> 00:48:57,455
- The number keeps increasing...
- Seriously.

1365
00:48:57,456 --> 00:48:59,095
the more famous he gets.

1366
00:48:59,096 --> 00:49:01,665
- They're here.
- He carries them around.

1367
00:49:01,666 --> 00:49:02,666
(Tae Sung's collection of glasses!)

1368
00:49:02,667 --> 00:49:05,135
Do you carry all these glasses whenever you go to shows?

1369
00:49:05,136 --> 00:49:08,435
I only carry six glasses with me.

1370
00:49:08,436 --> 00:49:09,605
I think I've seen these glasses quite frequently.

1371
00:49:09,606 --> 00:49:10,905
- This one.
- Right.

1372
00:49:10,906 --> 00:49:12,276
- This...
- He frequently wears round glasses.

1373
00:49:13,946 --> 00:49:16,015
(Choi Tae Sung's Optical Shop)

1374
00:49:16,016 --> 00:49:19,215
(Avant-garde design)

1375
00:49:19,216 --> 00:49:22,385
(Special price that your eyes can't look away)

1376
00:49:22,386 --> 00:49:23,386
- This...
- This is cute.

1377
00:49:23,387 --> 00:49:24,885
- Jung Hyun should wear this.
- I know, right?

1378
00:49:24,886 --> 00:49:26,756
I think Jung Hyun would also look good in glasses.

1379
00:49:28,656 --> 00:49:30,055
(A Japanese soldier in colonial Korea)

1380
00:49:30,056 --> 00:49:31,826
- Amazing.
- A Japanese soldier.

1381
00:49:31,896 --> 00:49:32,925
That's perfect.

1382
00:49:32,926 --> 00:49:35,935
(The Japanese soldier in colonial Korea starts yelling.)

1383
00:49:35,936 --> 00:49:38,536
There's a Japanese soldier! We have to run!

1384
00:49:38,636 --> 00:49:41,506
- We have to run away.
- He's a perfect actor.

1385
00:49:42,106 --> 00:49:44,546
He becomes an actor right after wearing the glasses!

1386
00:49:44,676 --> 00:49:46,045
- Right.
- That's amazing.

1387
00:49:46,046 --> 00:49:47,545
- Can we all try it?
- Can we try it on?

1388
00:49:47,546 --> 00:49:48,715
Of course.

1389
00:49:48,716 --> 00:49:50,475
- But...
- Kyung Hoon wears glasses a lot.

1390
00:49:50,476 --> 00:49:51,545
- It's an honor.
- That...

1391
00:49:51,546 --> 00:49:53,416
If you wear it the wrong way...

1392
00:49:53,516 --> 00:49:55,616
Hello, I'm the star lecturer Choi Tae Sung!

1393
00:49:55,886 --> 00:49:58,756
Choi Tae Sung! Star lecturer Choi Tae Sung!

1394
00:49:58,826 --> 00:50:00,656
I'll be teaching Korean history!

1395
00:50:01,156 --> 00:50:02,796
The Big Star of Korea!

1396
00:50:02,856 --> 00:50:04,796
Choi Tae Sung!

1397
00:50:05,696 --> 00:50:08,366
(Big Star and Small Star are all satisfied.)

1398
00:50:08,736 --> 00:50:11,036
(Fake Big Star's talent show, the end)

1399
00:50:11,136 --> 00:50:12,466
- There's a square one.
- This one...

1400
00:50:12,606 --> 00:50:14,705
This one is an edition.

1401
00:50:14,706 --> 00:50:16,335
- You look like a minion.
- Are they from the same brand?

1402
00:50:16,336 --> 00:50:18,706
- The same brand.
- Try these on.

1403
00:50:19,046 --> 00:50:20,445
- Write your name on the glasses.
- That would look nice.

1404
00:50:20,446 --> 00:50:21,775
- You could sign and sell them.
- It would look good on you.

1405
00:50:21,776 --> 00:50:24,115
I like glasses with some color in here.

1406
00:50:24,116 --> 00:50:25,446
- How do I look?
- They suit you well.

1407
00:50:25,486 --> 00:50:26,685
- They suit you so well.
- Do I look okay?

1408
00:50:26,686 --> 00:50:28,355
- That belong to Tae Sung.
- They suit him so well.

1409
00:50:28,356 --> 00:50:30,285
- Really?
- Give them to him as a gift.

1410
00:50:30,286 --> 00:50:31,925
- I'll send them to him.
- Come back.

1411
00:50:31,926 --> 00:50:33,625
- Give that to him.
- I should give him a new one.

1412
00:50:33,626 --> 00:50:35,555
- What are you doing? Go back.
- This is a good-quality one.

1413
00:50:35,556 --> 00:50:37,626
- The second period will start.
- New...

1414
00:50:37,966 --> 00:50:40,026
It suits him so well, so he gave it to him.

1415
00:50:40,726 --> 00:50:41,795
Anyway...

1416
00:50:41,796 --> 00:50:44,296
- But he...
- He doesn't...

1417
00:50:44,436 --> 00:50:48,035
He puts on many glasses with unique frames,

1418
00:50:48,036 --> 00:50:51,505
but he also wears lots of unique clothes in class.

1419
00:50:51,506 --> 00:50:54,205
Most of his shirts have cats...

1420
00:50:54,206 --> 00:50:56,675
- or dogs around the middle.
- He's a little like...

1421
00:50:56,676 --> 00:50:58,615
He's like Kim Gyeong Min in "Curious Paradise."

1422
00:50:58,616 --> 00:51:01,045
- For the students.
- He does all that...

1423
00:51:01,046 --> 00:51:02,685
- in consideration of his students.
- That's right.

1424
00:51:02,686 --> 00:51:04,525
- He wants to make it fun.
- Of course.

1425
00:51:04,526 --> 00:51:06,255
We talked about it in the beginning.

1426
00:51:06,256 --> 00:51:08,155
He will have a special lesson since it's National Liberation Day.

1427
00:51:08,156 --> 00:51:09,225
- Right.
- Yes.

1428
00:51:09,226 --> 00:51:10,295
The second lesson.

1429
00:51:10,296 --> 00:51:11,396
(Second lesson of National Liberation Day)

1430
00:51:11,626 --> 00:51:13,565
- Let's go!
- Yes!

1431
00:51:13,566 --> 00:51:15,096
Let's go!

1432
00:51:15,336 --> 00:51:17,496
What story will you tell us today?

1433
00:51:17,696 --> 00:51:19,805
How many years has it been since Liberation Day?

1434
00:51:19,806 --> 00:51:21,435
- It's the 80th year!
- It's the 80th year!

1435
00:51:21,436 --> 00:51:23,276
It was the 80th Liberation Day.

1436
00:51:24,006 --> 00:51:26,345
I actually came here today...

1437
00:51:26,346 --> 00:51:28,376
because I wanted to tell you this.

1438
00:51:29,246 --> 00:51:32,045
I don't want us to say, "It's the 80th Liberation Day..."

1439
00:51:32,046 --> 00:51:35,115
and just move on.

1440
00:51:35,116 --> 00:51:36,615
I want it to be different.

1441
00:51:36,616 --> 00:51:39,055
I want us to act differently.

1442
00:51:39,056 --> 00:51:42,055
I would like to share that with you.

1443
00:51:42,056 --> 00:51:44,026
So this is a very happy day,

1444
00:51:44,226 --> 00:51:45,895
but I want us to know why.

1445
00:51:45,896 --> 00:51:47,096
Repeat after me.

1446
00:51:47,566 --> 00:51:48,695
Let's be happy about National Liberation Day...

1447
00:51:48,696 --> 00:51:49,865
with knowledge!

1448
00:51:49,866 --> 00:51:51,235
Let's be happy about National Liberation Day...

1449
00:51:51,236 --> 00:51:52,405
with knowledge!

1450
00:51:52,406 --> 00:51:53,635
One more time. Let's be happy about National Liberation Day...

1451
00:51:53,636 --> 00:51:54,706
with knowledge!

1452
00:51:54,806 --> 00:51:55,905
Let's be happy about National Liberation Day...

1453
00:51:55,906 --> 00:51:56,975
with knowledge!

1454
00:51:56,976 --> 00:51:58,006
Great.

1455
00:51:58,106 --> 00:52:01,445
The story about National Liberation Day I will share today...

1456
00:52:01,446 --> 00:52:03,215
is about ordinary people...

1457
00:52:03,216 --> 00:52:05,485
whose stories weren't put in textbooks.

1458
00:52:05,486 --> 00:52:07,986
The story of August 15, 1945,

1459
00:52:08,056 --> 00:52:11,425
that those ordinary people made.

1460
00:52:11,426 --> 00:52:13,355
I will share that with you.

1461
00:52:13,356 --> 00:52:15,156
(The story of August 15, 1945, that ordinary people made)

1462
00:52:15,756 --> 00:52:17,855
Before sharing this story,

1463
00:52:17,856 --> 00:52:19,996
I will show you a picture.

1464
00:52:20,866 --> 00:52:22,995
- This is a very famous picture.
- I've seen this a lot.

1465
00:52:22,996 --> 00:52:24,166
You've seen this many times.

1466
00:52:24,266 --> 00:52:26,605
You must have seen it in textbooks...

1467
00:52:26,606 --> 00:52:28,405
or in the news.

1468
